item.title: Acacia gunnii
item.dc:creator: russell
item.description: Pretty sure this is the first record of this species on the Vic. Volcanic Plains. Growing in typical habitat for this species; ie. dry, rocky site, lacking taller shrubs, relatively large distances between grass tussocks.

item.title: Grevillea rosmarinifolia
item.dc:creator: russell
item.description: Foliage is quite flexible, with a slight sharpness to the tip. Growing on a cliff face / escarpment with fully grown Bursaria, Callitris and other fully grown plants. I mention fully grown because the attached (3 plants seen) was 50cm tall by 1m wide (possibly a bit less). Plants were very woody so probably old. There are no plants above the escarpment, which was Grey Box with wildflower understorey. There are no grevilleas recorded anywhere near here. It is a form of rosmarinifolia.

item.title: Allocasuarina verticillata

item.description: Single old female plant surrounded by many young plants, all female. No male in this copse. The 'fruit' pictured are actually galls, probably Cylindrococcus (Hemiptera).

item.title: Allocasuarina verticillata
item.dc:creator: russell
item.description: Male plant. This species is now locally rare owing to habitat destruction. The few remaining plants appear to be restricted to rail reserves (grassy plains woodland). Possibly no longer a viable remnant population?
